TX had and odd reporting day: although TX DSHS reported 3,964 new cases for 22 September 2020, they also announce the following: "13,622 older cases recently reported by labs were included in the statewide total but excluded from statewide and Harris County new confirmed cases (507)." This meant a new cases-number of 17,820 new cases for Texas on 22 Sep according to covidtracking.com's kind of counting, although that might - for this question - be a bit unfair, since the older cases may already date back to August or even earlier. However, Texas surpassed the outstanding number of confirmations, 10,281 just yesterday and politely reminds us that revisions of testing and/or methodology, belated test results, error correction etc. can have a significant influence on the states' result and thus on the total question resolution.

This could have some influence for this question, so shifting minimally down: "DSHS revised its method for reporting Total Tests, effective 9/14/2020. DSHS will now only report electronic lab results that have passed quality checks and have cleared into the state’s system of record, NEDSS, the National Electronic Disease Surveillance System. This improvement is possible due to recent upgrades to NEDSS, which now processes data more quickly. The revised methodology ensures data is fully deduplicated and that only tests that passed through the data submission quality checks are counted in Total Tests. Test submissions that error out of the system due to data quality issues will not be counted until they are successfully resubmitted and pass validation requirements. I fitted AR models to each of the 55 states in this calculation and predicted the total case count for the month of September and then compared them to new case counts in June 2020. I get an EV of 39 states. 1 state is in the 0 to 100 higher (compared to June) estimate category, 1 state is in the 250 to 500 higher estimate category, 3 states are in the 500 to 1000 higher estimate category and 34 states are in the 1,000 higher estimate category. Thus we have at least 34 states that we deem as "safe" estimates (i.e. Sept. case counts will likely be higher than June). It is very unlikely that we will see less than 27 states and more than 44 states based on the number of edge cases (e.g. the number of states whose September numbers are less than June numbers by a max of 500 is zero). Thus, we put most of the weight in 36 - 43 bucket with some probability in the 28 - 35 bucket.

Some adjustments are in order to account for the considerable variance in the data at the state level as we enter the home stretch - correction in MA on Sep 1st for example almost guaranteed to put Sep under Jun no matter what (negative 7k).

The COVID Tracking Project website data by state will determine the outcome of this challenge. We can do the following calculation fairly easily. Yes, it's a bit tedious, but shouldn't take more than about half an hour. Subtract the cumulative number of positive tests on May 31 from the cumulative number of positive tests on June 30. It's the data column labeled "cases." Call the result J. Divide the answer by 30 to get the average number of new cases for the month of June for each state.

First, to establish a baseline - we should check how many states daily new cases are above June levels. Based on the NYTimes state-level maps, 43 states are currently seeing daily new cases on the rise. For almost all of these states, daily new cases are above levels seen in June because the end of May was the trough of the 'first wave' before reopening in most of those states. Next, we should check what the lifecycle of a case resurgence looks like. Based on the initial wave of cases in the states with the most serious outbreaks (NY, CT, NJ, DC etc.) a cycle takes above 2-3 months to run its course with a reasonable amount of variance. Thus, we can expect states that started to resurge in mid-June as reopening commenced to be at the tail end of their cycles. This would cause us to move our estimate downwards from the baseline of low-40's. But two important context specific factors bake me keep my distribution centered fairly high in the upper 30's. First, though some states like California have been willing to reinstitute lockdown policies due to the second wave, most other state governors have not been willing to do so. Still, even if lockdown-esque policies are put in place, rates of testing are much higher so even if test-positivity rates are lower, the raw number of cases will be higher than before simply because we are catching more cases. The policy variable does add the most uncertainty to my estimate though which is why I put decent probability on all outcomes from 12-35 states below my max of 36-43. State governors are increasingly encouraging the use of masks and mask usage in the US is on the rise. It is possible that as masks become more widespread, we reach a point at which we see substantial reductions in new cases without states having to go into full lockdowns. This variable is uncertain both from a policy perspective, a cultural perspective, and a public health efficacy perspective.

I have adjusted my forecast based on new information between Jun. 28th and Jul. 11th. Around the end of June 2020 we observed a sharp increase in COVID-19 cases and it continuously break daily new cases record. Yesterday, July 11th, we have seen over 70k new COVID cases across United States. It is still unknown to us how the second wave will play out and how long the new cases increase will last. However, even if the upward trend for new cases is quickly controlled, it doesn’t mean new cases will disappear overnight. Based on the first wave reaction in United States, we observe that the new cases capped around April 1st and hovered at essentially the same level for about 2 months and a half. Right now, state governments are essentially doing similar things to manage the spread of second wave COVID, as they do to manage the first wave. Therefore, it is highly probable that we will observe the new cases curve plateaued (higher daily number than June 2020) rather than sharply dropped to zero and I assign such probability 70%. In this case, if we assume all states are independent, then the base mean for the number of states to have higher number of cases in September than June is 38.5. So I put my initial distribution’s mean around that number.

Estimates for individual states based on the current trend. However, the probabilities for individual states should be highly correlated as are the number of positive test cases. The highest variance assuming independence of probabilities for states is just 13.75 while the highest possible variance is 252 (assuming uniform distribution across all possible states). Without dependence, the extreme cases will be extremely unlikely which is unreasonable given that there is a lot of variability in the possible scenarios that can occur in the next 2 months (although they still should be considered improbable). Also, the eventual increase in the test numbers should increase the number of positives which would otherwise be undetected because of the lack of symptoms. Many states with a low or moderate number of test cases might focus more on opening the economy which will result in the increase of cases (even if it will be tiny, it will still count towards the forecasted value) - this suggests that the mean of the distribution should be rather high (around 20). The specific probabilities are derived through the MC simulation based on simple assumptions and rough estimates.

Infection rates are already going up, with most states now reopening to various degrees. The question is how local governments and individuals will respond to these increases. I believe “pandemic fatigue” will be a significant factor in the decisions for both, particularly as we become more accustomed to (and comfortable with) routine reports of deaths in the thousands. The course of the pandemic so far suggests that undetected (untested and never reported) community spread can require a significant time period (months) before resulting in the kind of widespread transmission that can’t be overlooked. Testing and and contract tracing are the key tools to avoid this trap, but there isn’t nearly enough of it occurring, and that seems likely to persist, given the lack of support and coordination being offered by our federal government. More cases in September than June is a pretty low bar to clear, so I am fairly confident that it will be the case in most places. The bigger unknown is how testing will unfold. It’s unfortunate, but in some states, political beliefs could have a significant impact on whether sufferers choose to be tested and counted, as is already the case with the use of face masks. Testing in general may fall out of favor in some states, with availability poor and political incentives to keep it that way. The other uncertainty for me involves timing. Numbers may or may not dip in the summer, with people often outdoors. And random chance will also play its part, given the proportion of COVID-19 transmission that can be attributed to individual superspreader events. September may be too specific a time frame for the overall trends I expect to see.

Interesting question. Initial impression: 1) what will case totals be for June? My guess is that in general they will be much lower for most states than for April and May. My guess is that we will still be benefiting from social distancing and people taking this seriously. 2) what will the case totals be for September? Much harder to estimate. My guess is that in general they will be about the same as in June or higher as people let down their guard on social distancing and start working and vacationing more. Still, I think having nearly all states higher in Sept than in June also seems unlikely.

The epidemiology suggests that while a number of states will successfully indent their numbers, some won’t. So, most likely the states with more densely populated areas will have a harder time of things as opposed to others.
